Dataset:

The dataset presents an extensive collection of around 24.4 million credit card transactions, sourced from IBM's financial database. Capturing a wide spectrum of user interactions, the data provides a detailed snapshot of transaction behaviors, patterns, and potential vulnerabilities. Details include: User&card info, time&amount of transactions, merchant details, fraud detection flag.

Methodology:

  • Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA): Analyze trends, gain insights into fraudulant transaction behaviors and system vulnerabilities.
  • Predictive Modelling: Develop models based on past fraudulent transactions to predict and mitigate future fraud, aiming to enhance overall security and user trust.

The card_id represents a single card associated with one user. Since a single user can possess multiple cards, each card will have its own unique card_id in this context. To address this, we will create a new column by concatenating the User and Card columns, providing a combined identifier for analysis.

EDA¶

To derive meaningful insights into fraud cases, we isolate this subset of data for Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA). This focused approach enables a deeper examination and understanding of the patterns and behaviors associated with fraudulent activity.

In [14]:
fraud_data = df[df['Is Fraud?'] == 1]

Transaction Amount¶

In [15]:

The majority of fraudulent transactions fall within the amount range of 0 to 250, highlighting a tendency for fraud to occur more frequently in lower-value transactions.

The State column includes a mix of U.S. states and other countries, revealing distinct geographical patterns:

  • At the country level: Italy, Algeria, Haiti, and Mexico emerge as significant hotspots for fraudulent activities.
  • Among U.S. states: Ohio, California, and Florida report the highest incidences of fraud.

From the above chart we see that our data lacks sufficient positive fraud cases (i.e. Is Fraud = 1) for our model to effectively learn to classify transactions. This signals that we may need to class balancing the dataset.

Generally in this case undersampling would be recommended as we have a large dataset [24 mn] of which only 0.1% are fraudulent.

Since we are using RF this may be a moot point but we will test various scenerios to establish the best model

# Calculate the number of fraud transactions
fraud_sample = rf[rf['Is Fraud?'] == 1]

# Calculate the number of non-fraud transactions to fill the remaining sample
sample_size = 100000  # desired sample size
non_fraud_sample_size = sample_size - len(fraud_sample)

# Sample from non-fraudulent transactions
non_fraud_sample = rf[rf['Is Fraud?'] == 0].sample(n=non_fraud_sample_size, random_state=42)

# Combine all fraudulent transactions with the sampled non-fraudulent transactions
sampled_rf = pd.concat([fraud_sample, non_fraud_sample])

# Shuffle the sampled DataFrame
sampled_rf = sampled_rf.sample(frac=1, random_state=42).reset_index(drop=True)

# Print the shape of the resulting sampled DataFrame
print(sampled_rf.shape)
del rf

Logistic Regression¶

In [39]:
results["Experiment1"] = {}
results["Experiment1"]["Model"] = "Logistic Regression"

# Start time
start_time = time.time()

# Split dataset into features and target
X = sampled_rf.drop(columns=['Is Fraud?'])
y = sampled_rf['Is Fraud?']

# Train-test split
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42)


# Scale features
sc = StandardScaler()
X_train = sc.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test = sc.transform(X_test)

# Define the parameter grid for Logistic Regression
param_grid = {
    'penalty': ['l1', 'l2', 'elasticnet'],  # Regularization type
    'C': [0.01, 0.1, 1, 10, 100],                  # Regularization strength
    'solver': ['lbfgs', 'liblinear', 'saga'],      # Optimization algorithms
    'max_iter': [100, 200, 500]                    # Maximum iterations
}

# Initialize the Logistic Regression model
log_reg = LogisticRegression(random_state=42, class_weight='balanced')

# Initialize GridSearchCV
grid_search_lr = GridSearchCV(
    estimator=log_reg,
    param_grid=param_grid,
    scoring='f1',         # Optimize for F1 score since fraud detection prioritizes balanced precision and recall
    cv=3,                 # 3-fold cross-validation
    verbose=0,
    n_jobs=-1             # Use all available cores
)

# Fit the GridSearchCV on training data
grid_search_lr.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Best parameters
print("Best parameters:", grid_search_lr.best_params_)

# Best Logistic Regression model
best_lr_model = grid_search_lr.best_estimator_

# Evaluate on the test set
y_pred_lr = best_lr_model.predict(X_test)
y_proba_lr = best_lr_model.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]  # Probabilities for ROC

# Metrics Calculation
accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_lr)
precision = precision_score(y_test, y_pred_lr, average='binary', pos_label=1)
recall = recall_score(y_test, y_pred_lr, average='binary', pos_label=1)
f1 = f1_score(y_test, y_pred_lr, average='binary', pos_label=1)

# Print metrics
print("\nMetrics:")
print(f'Accuracy: {accuracy:.2f}')
print(f'Precision: {precision:.2f}')
print(f'Recall: {recall:.2f}')
print(f'F1 Score: {f1:.2f}')

# Print classification report
print("\nClassification Report:")
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred_lr))

cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred_lr)
sns.heatmap(
    cm,
    annot=True,
    cmap='Blues',
    fmt='g',
    xticklabels=['Non-Fraud', 'Fraud'],
    yticklabels=['Non-Fraud', 'Fraud']
)
plt.xlabel('Predicted')
plt.ylabel('True')
plt.title('Confusion Matrix')

results["Experiment5"] = {}
results["Experiment5"]["Model"] = "Neural Network"

# Start time
start_time = time.time()

# Check if GPU is available
device = torch.device("cuda" if torch.cuda.is_available() else "cpu")
print(f"Using device: {device}")

# Split the data
X = sampled_rf.drop(columns=['Is Fraud?'])
y = sampled_rf['Is Fraud?']

# Assume X and y are your preprocessed features and target variable
# Standardize the data
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)  # Assume X is your feature set

# Split the data into training and testing sets
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_scaled, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42)

# Convert data to PyTorch tensors and move to GPU if available
X_train_tensor = torch.tensor(X_train, dtype=torch.float32).to(device)
X_test_tensor = torch.tensor(X_test, dtype=torch.float32).to(device)
y_train_tensor = torch.tensor(y_train.values, dtype=torch.float32).view(-1, 1).to(device)
y_test_tensor = torch.tensor(y_test.values, dtype=torch.float32).view(-1, 1).to(device)

# Create DataLoader for batch processing
train_dataset = TensorDataset(X_train_tensor, y_train_tensor)
test_dataset = TensorDataset(X_test_tensor, y_test_tensor)

batch_size = 64  # Batch size
train_loader = DataLoader(train_dataset, batch_size=batch_size, shuffle=True)
test_loader = DataLoader(test_dataset, batch_size=batch_size, shuffle=False)

# Define the Neural Network architecture
class FraudDetectionNN(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self):
        super(FraudDetectionNN, self).__init__()
        self.layer1 = nn.Linear(X_train.shape[1], 128)  # First layer with 128 neurons
        self.layer2 = nn.Linear(128, 64)  # Second layer with 64 neurons
        self.layer3 = nn.Linear(64, 32)  # Third layer with 32 neurons
        self.layer4 = nn.Linear(32, 1)  # Output layer with 1 neuron (binary classification)
        self.relu = nn.ReLU()  # ReLU activation function
        self.sigmoid = nn.Sigmoid()  # Sigmoid for output layer to output probabilities

    def forward(self, x):
        x = self.relu(self.layer1(x))
        x = self.relu(self.layer2(x))
        x = self.relu(self.layer3(x))
        x = self.sigmoid(self.layer4(x))
        return x

# Initialize the model, loss function, and optimizer
model = FraudDetectionNN().to(device)
criterion = nn.BCELoss()  # Binary Cross-Entropy Loss
optimizer = optim.Adam(model.parameters(), lr=0.001)  # Adam optimizer

# Early Stopping
best_f1 = 0.0
patience = 5
epochs_without_improvement = 0

# Train the model
num_epochs = 50
train_losses = []  # Store the loss during training

for epoch in range(num_epochs):
    model.train()  # Set the model to training mode
    running_loss = 0.0
    
    for inputs, labels in train_loader:
        optimizer.zero_grad()  # Zero the gradients
        outputs = model(inputs)  # Forward pass
        loss = criterion(outputs, labels)  # Calculate loss
        loss.backward()  # Backward pass
        optimizer.step()  # Update weights
        
        running_loss += loss.item()

    avg_train_loss = running_loss / len(train_loader)
    train_losses.append(avg_train_loss)

    print(f'Epoch [{epoch+1}/{num_epochs}], Loss: {avg_train_loss:.4f}')

    # Early stopping check (based on F1 score)
    model.eval()  # Set the model to evaluation mode
    y_pred_prob = model(X_test_tensor)
    y_pred = (y_pred_prob > 0.5).float()
    
    f1 = f1_score(y_test_tensor.cpu(), y_pred.cpu())
    if f1 > best_f1:
        best_f1 = f1
        epochs_without_improvement = 0
    else:
        epochs_without_improvement += 1

    if epochs_without_improvement >= patience:
        print("Early stopping due to no improvement in F1 score.")
        break

# Plot the training loss
plt.plot(train_losses, label="Training Loss")
plt.xlabel('Epochs')
plt.ylabel('Loss')
plt.title('Training Loss Over Epochs')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

# Evaluate the model
model.eval()  # Set the model to evaluation mode

# Make predictions on the test set
y_pred_prob = model(X_test_tensor)
y_pred = (y_pred_prob > 0.5).float()

# Calculate metrics
accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test_tensor.cpu(), y_pred.cpu())
precision = precision_score(y_test_tensor.cpu(), y_pred.cpu())
recall = recall_score(y_test_tensor.cpu(), y_pred.cpu())

class ImprovedFraudGNN(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, input_dim, hidden_dim):
        super(ImprovedFraudGNN, self).__init__()
        self.fc1 = nn.Linear(input_dim, hidden_dim)
        self.fc2 = nn.Linear(hidden_dim, hidden_dim)
        self.fc3 = nn.Linear(hidden_dim, hidden_dim // 2)
        self.fc4 = nn.Linear(hidden_dim // 2, 1)

        self.dropout = nn.Dropout(0.5)  # Prevent overfitting
        self.batch_norm1 = nn.BatchNorm1d(hidden_dim)
        self.batch_norm2 = nn.BatchNorm1d(hidden_dim)
        self.batch_norm3 = nn.BatchNorm1d(hidden_dim // 2)

    def forward(self, x):
        x = F.relu(self.batch_norm1(self.fc1(x)))
        x = self.dropout(x)
        x = F.relu(self.batch_norm2(self.fc2(x)))
        x = self.dropout(x)
        x = F.relu(self.batch_norm3(self.fc3(x)))
        x = self.fc4(x)
        return x

y_train = y_train.view(-1, 1)
y_valid = y_valid.view(-1, 1)
# Train the model
for i in range(num_epochs):
    # Forward pass
    output = model(x_train)
    # Compute the training loss
    loss = criterion(output, y_train)
    
    # Compute accuracy for training set
    predictions = torch.sigmoid(output)
    predicted_labels = (predictions > 0.4).float()
    accuracy = torch.mean((predicted_labels == y_train).float())
    
    if i % 20 == 0:
        print(f'Epoch: {i}, Train Loss: {loss.item()}, Train Accuracy: {accuracy.item()}')
    
        # Validation forward pass
        val_output = model(x_valid)
        val_loss = criterion(val_output, y_valid)
        val_losses.append(val_loss.item())
    
    # Zero the gradients
    optimizer.zero_grad()
    # Perform backpropagation
    loss.backward()
    # Update the parameters
    optimizer.step()
    
    train_losses.append(loss.item())

# Extracting metrics and model names
experiments = [results[exp]['Model'] for exp in results.keys()]
accuracy = [results[exp]['Accuracy'] for exp in results.keys()]
precision = [results[exp]['Precision'] for exp in results.keys()]
recall = [results[exp]['Recall'] for exp in results.keys()]
f1_score = [results[exp]['F1-Score'] for exp in results.keys()]

# Extract training times as numeric values
train_time = [float(results[exp]['Train Time'].split()[0]) for exp in results.keys()]

# Normalize training time to bring it to the same scale as other metrics (0-1)
max_train_time = max(train_time)
min_train_time = min(train_time)
normalized_train_time = [(t - min_train_time) / (max_train_time - min_train_time) for t in train_time]

# Metrics
labels = ['Accuracy', 'Precision', 'Recall', 'F1-Score', 'Training Time']
metrics = [accuracy, precision, recall, f1_score, normalized_train_time]

# Number of experiments
num_experiments = len(experiments)

# Set up radar chart
angles = np.linspace(0, 2 * np.pi, len(labels), endpoint=False).tolist()
angles += angles[:1]  # Ensure closing of the radar chart

# Create the plot
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 8), subplot_kw=dict(polar=True))

# Plot each experiment
for i, experiment in enumerate(experiments):
    data = [accuracy[i], precision[i], recall[i], f1_score[i], normalized_train_time[i]]
    data += data[:1]  # Close the loop
    ax.plot(angles, data, label=experiment, linewidth=2, linestyle='solid')
    ax.fill(angles, data, alpha=0.25)

# Set the labels for each axis
ax.set_xticks(angles[:-1])
ax.set_xticklabels(labels)

# Add a legend
ax.legend(loc='upper right', bbox_to_anchor=(1.2, 1))

# Title
plt.title('Model Comparison Across Different Experiments', size=16)

# Display the plot
plt.show()
